1	\chapter{Sheaves of $k$-modules: sheafification, Ext, and the structure sheaf as a sheaf of $k$-modules}
2	\label{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafModuleK}
3	
4	This chapter implements Phase~A step~5 of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}: equipping $H^1(C, \struct C)$ with a $k$-vector-space structure when $C$ is a scheme over $\Spec k$. The route is through Mathlib's general $\Linear k$ enrichment of $\Sheaf(\opens X, \ModuleCat k)$ together with \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.instModule}, which automatically provides $\Module k$ on $\Ext$ groups in any $\Linear k$ abelian category. The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every instance and definition here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $H^1(C, \struct C)$ in Definition~\ref{def:genus}.
5	
6	The chapter is split into two sections of work. Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs} and~\ref{sec:moduleK_ext} (the iteration~005 work) provide the typeclass plumbing — the $\HasSheafify$ and $\HasExt$ instances on $\Sheaf(\opens X, \ModuleCat k)$. Section~\ref{sec:scheme_toModuleKSheaf} (the iteration~006 work) provides the \emph{substantive} content of Phase~A step~5: the $\ModuleCat k$-valued structure sheaf $\toModuleKSheaf C$ for $C : \mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec k)$, viewing $\struct C$ as a sheaf of $k$-modules via the structure morphism. Together these complete Phase~A step~5; the final remaining piece for an honest definition of $\genus C$ as $\dim_k H^1(C, \struct C)$ is then Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, multi-iteration).
7	
8	A discovery probe of Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} (logged in \texttt{task\_pending.md}) confirms that the four typeclass pieces of Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext} are already in Mathlib (no new mathematical content; only universe-pinned packaging) and that the eight pieces of Section~\ref{sec:scheme_toModuleKSheaf} type-check end-to-end (~80 LOC; one short proof per piece). After this chapter lands, the typeclass chain \[ \HasSheafify \to \HasExt \to \Linear k \to \mathtt{Ext.instModule} \] is in place and $\toModuleKSheaf C$ provides the actual carrier on which it operates; the $\Module k$ instance on $H^1(C, \struct C) := (\toModuleKSheaf C).\mathtt H\,1$ is then automatic.
9	
10	\section{Sheafification of $\ModuleCat k$-valued sheaves on opens}
11	\label{sec:moduleK_prereqs}
12	
13	\begin{theorem}[Sheafification on the topology of opens, $\ModuleCat k$-valued]
14	  \label{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
15	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
16	  \leanok
17	  Let $k$ be a commutative ring and $X$ a topological space. Then the Grothendieck topology of opens of $X$ has
18	  \[
19	    \mathtt{HasSheafify}(\opens(X), \ModuleCat\, k).
20	  \]
21	\end{theorem}
22	
23	\begin{proof}
24	  \leanok
25	  Mathlib's general sheafification API constructs \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} whenever \lstinline{HasWeakSheafify J A} holds and the resulting sheafification preserves finite limits. For \lstinline{J = Opens.grothendieckTopology X} and \lstinline{A = ModuleCat k} both prerequisites are wired in Mathlib (small-site sheafification on a concrete category, plus exactness of $\ModuleCat k$-valued sheafification). The instance is therefore inferable; the prover's task is to reproduce the universe pinning that succeeded for the iter-004 $\AddCommGrpCat$ analogue (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_AddCommGrp}).
26	\end{proof}
27	
28	\section{$\Ext$ for $\ModuleCat k$-valued sheaves on opens}
29	\label{sec:moduleK_ext}
30	
31	\begin{theorem}[$\Ext$ on the topology of opens, $\ModuleCat k$-valued]
32	  \label{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
33	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
34	  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
35	  \leanok
36	  Let $k$ be a commutative ring and $X$ a topological space. Then the category $\Sheaf(\opens(X), \ModuleCat k)$ has
37	  \[
38	    \mathtt{HasExt.\{u+1\}}\bigl(\Sheaf(\opens(X), \ModuleCat k)\bigr).
39	  \]
40	\end{theorem}
41	
42	\begin{proof}
43	  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
44	  \leanok
45	  $\ModuleCat k$ is abelian. The sheaf category $\Sheaf(J, A)$ inherits an abelian structure from an abelian $A$ once \lstinline{HasSheafify J A} holds (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}). Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard} produces a \lstinline{HasExt} instance from any abelian category. The universe annotation \lstinline{HasExt.\{u+1\}} matches the unique morphism universe of \lstinline{Sheaf (Opens.gT X) (ModuleCat.\{u\} k)}, mirroring the iter-004 $\AddCommGrpCat$ analogue (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_AddCommGrp}).
46	\end{proof}
47	
48	\section{The structure sheaf of a $\Spec k$-scheme as a sheaf of $k$-modules}
49	\label{sec:scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
50	
51	This section provides the substantive content of Phase~A step~5: for $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, equipping the structure sheaf $\struct C$ with a sheaf-of-$k$-modules structure via the algebra map induced by the structure morphism $C.\mathrm{hom} : C.\mathrm{left} \to \Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k)$. Together with the typeclass plumbing of Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext} and Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.instModule}, this completes the typeclass chain that gives $H^1(C, \struct C)$ a $\Module k$ structure.
52	
53	\subsection{The algebra map from the structure morphism}
54	
55	For each open $U \subseteq C.\mathrm{left}$, the structure morphism induces a chain of ring maps
56	\[
57	  k \xrightarrow{(\Gamma\!\Spec\!\mathrm{Iso}\,k)^{-1}} \Gamma(\Spec\,k, \top) \xrightarrow{C.\mathrm{hom}.\mathrm{app}\,\top} \Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, C.\mathrm{hom}^{-1}\top) \xrightarrow{\rho} \Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U),
58	\]
59	where $\rho$ is the restriction along $U \le C.\mathrm{hom}^{-1}\top = \top$. Mathlib's \lstinline{Scheme.\Gamma SpecIso} provides the first iso, and the rest is the ordinary \lstinline{Scheme.Hom.app} together with the action of the presheaf on the inclusion $U \le \top$.
60	
61	\begin{definition}[Algebra map on a section]
62	  \label{def:Scheme_kToSection}
63	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.kToSection}
64	  \uses{def:Scheme_toAbSheaf}
65	  Let $k$ be a commutative ring and $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$. For any open $U$ of $C.\mathrm{left}$, define
66	  \[
67	    \mathtt{kToSection}\,C\,U \;\colon\; \CommRingCat\,k \;\longrightarrow\; \Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U)
68	  \]
69	  to be the composition $(\Gamma\!\Spec\!\mathrm{Iso}\,(\CommRingCat\,k))^{-1} \circ (C.\mathrm{hom}.\mathrm{app}\,\top) \circ \rho$, where $\rho$ is the restriction map of $C.\mathrm{left}$ from $\top$ to $U$.
70	\end{definition}
71	
72	\begin{definition}[Algebra structure on a section]
73	  \label{def:Scheme_algebraSection}
74	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.algebraSection}
75	  \uses{def:Scheme_kToSection}
76	  The ring map $\mathtt{kToSection}\,C\,U$ exhibits $\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U)$ as a $k$-algebra. We register the resulting $\Algebra\,k\,(\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U))$ instance via \lstinline{RingHom.toAlgebra}.
77	\end{definition}
78	
79	\begin{lemma}[Defining identity for the algebra map]
80	  \label{lem:Scheme_algebraMap_eq_kToSection}
81	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.algebraMap_eq_kToSection}
82	  \uses{def:Scheme_algebraSection}
83	  Under the algebra structure of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_algebraSection},
84	  \[
85	    \mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,(\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U)) \;=\; (\mathtt{kToSection}\,C\,U).\mathrm{hom}.
86	  \]
87	\end{lemma}
88	
89	\begin{proof}
90	  \uses{def:Scheme_algebraSection}
91	  Definitionally true: \lstinline{RingHom.toAlgebra}$\,(f).\mathrm{algebraMap} = f$.
92	\end{proof}
93	
94	\subsection{Naturality of the algebra map}
95	
96	\begin{lemma}[Restriction is compatible with the algebra map]
97	  \label{lem:Scheme_kToSection_naturality}
98	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.kToSection_naturality}
99	  \uses{def:Scheme_kToSection}
100	  For any $f : U \to V$ in $\opens(C.\mathrm{left})^{\mathrm{op}}$ (i.e.\ $V \le U$ in $\opens(C.\mathrm{left})$),
101	  \[
102	    \mathtt{kToSection}\,C\,U \,\circ\, C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{presheaf}.\mathrm{map}\,f \;=\; \mathtt{kToSection}\,C\,V.
103	  \]
104	\end{lemma}
105	
106	\begin{proof}
107	  \uses{def:Scheme_kToSection}
108	  Both sides factor through $C.\mathrm{hom}.\mathrm{app}\,\top : \Gamma(\Spec k, \top) \to \Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, \top)$. The remaining triangle on $\opens(C.\mathrm{left})$ commutes by functoriality of $C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{presheaf}$ on the composable inclusions $V \le U \le \top$.
109	\end{proof}
110	
111	\begin{lemma}[Algebra-map naturality]
112	  \label{lem:Scheme_algebraMap_naturality}
113	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf.algebraMap_naturality}
114	  \uses{lem:Scheme_kToSection_naturality, lem:Scheme_algebraMap_eq_kToSection}
115	  For any $f : U \to V$ in $\opens(C.\mathrm{left})^{\mathrm{op}}$ and $r \in k$,
116	  \[
117	    (C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{presheaf}.\mathrm{map}\,f).\mathrm{hom}\bigl(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,(\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U))\,r\bigr) \;=\; \mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,(\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, V))\,r.
118	  \]
119	\end{lemma}
120	
121	\begin{proof}
122	  \uses{lem:Scheme_kToSection_naturality, lem:Scheme_algebraMap_eq_kToSection}
123	  Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_algebraMap_eq_kToSection} reduces both sides to the underlying ring map of $\mathtt{kToSection}$; Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_kToSection_naturality} then closes the goal by congruence.
124	\end{proof}
125	
126	\subsection{The presheaf of $k$-modules and its sheaf condition}
127	
128	\begin{definition}[Presheaf of $k$-modules from $\struct C$]
129	  \label{def:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf}
130	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKPresheaf}
131	  \uses{def:Scheme_algebraSection, lem:Scheme_algebraMap_naturality}
132	  Define the presheaf
133	  \[
134	    \mathtt{toModuleKPresheaf}\,C \;\colon\; \opens(C.\mathrm{left})^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \ModuleCat\,k
135	  \]
136	  by
137	  \[
138	    \mathtt{toModuleKPresheaf}\,C \,.\,\mathrm{obj}\,U \;:=\; \ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,(\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U)),
139	  \]
140	  with the action of $k$ given by the algebra structure of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_algebraSection}, and on a morphism $f : U \to V$ by the restriction map $(C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{presheaf}.\mathrm{map}\,f).\mathrm{hom}$, viewed as a $k$-linear map. The action on morphisms is well-defined because the underlying ring map preserves $+$ and is $k$-linear by the naturality lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_algebraMap_naturality}: $\rho(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,r \cdot x) = \rho(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,r) \cdot \rho(x) = \mathtt{algebraMap}\,r \cdot \rho(x)$. Functoriality reduces to $C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{presheaf}.\mathrm{map\_id}$ and \lstinline{map_comp}.
141	\end{definition}
142	
143	\begin{theorem}[Sheaf condition]
144	  \label{thm:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf_isSheaf}
145	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKPresheaf_isSheaf}
146	  \uses{def:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf, thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK}
147	  $\mathtt{toModuleKPresheaf}\,C$ is a sheaf for the Grothendieck topology $\Opens.\mathrm{grothendieckTopology}\,C.\mathrm{left}.\mathrm{toTopCat}$.
148	\end{theorem}
149	
150	\begin{proof}
151	  \uses{def:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf}
152	  By the concrete-category criterion \lstinline{Presheaf.isSheaf_iff_isSheaf_forget} applied to the forgetful functor $\ModuleCat\,k \to \Type$, it suffices to show that $\mathtt{toModuleKPresheaf}\,C \,\circ\, \mathrm{forget}\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$ is a sheaf in $\Type$. By construction, this composite agrees on objects and morphisms with $C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{presheaf} \,\circ\, \mathrm{forget}\,\CommRingCat$. The latter is a sheaf in $\Type$ because $C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{sheaf}$ is a sheaf in $\CommRingCat$ and \lstinline{Presheaf.isSheaf_iff_isSheaf_forget} also applies on the $\CommRingCat$ side.
153	\end{proof}
154	
155	\subsection{The structure sheaf as a sheaf of $k$-modules}
156	
157	\begin{definition}[Structure sheaf as a sheaf of $k$-modules]
158	  \label{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
159	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf}
160	  \uses{def:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf, thm:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf_isSheaf}
161	  Bundle Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf} and Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_toModuleKPresheaf_isSheaf} into the sheaf
162	  \[
163	    \mathtt{toModuleKSheaf}\,C \;\colon\; \Sheaf\bigl(\opens(C.\mathrm{left}.\mathrm{toTopCat}),\ \ModuleCat\,k\bigr).
164	  \]
165	\end{definition}
166	
167	\section{Use in the project}
168	
169	The composition of the four typeclass instances of Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext} with Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf} delivers Phase~A step~5 in full:
170	
171	\begin{itemize}
172	  \item For $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, the cohomology
173	    \[
174	      H^n(C, \struct C) \;:=\; (\mathtt{toModuleKSheaf}\,C).\mathtt{H}\,n
175	    \]
176	    is well-defined and automatically carries a $\Module\,k$ instance via \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.instModule} ($\Linear\,k$-enrichment auto-inferable on the $\ModuleCat\,k$-valued sheaf category, so $\Ext$ groups are themselves $\Module\,k$).
177	  \item The forgetful functor $\ModuleCat\,k \to \AddCommGrpCat$ recovers the iter-004 abelian-group cohomology, so $\mathtt{toModuleKSheaf}$ commutes with $\mathtt{toAbSheaf}$ on the underlying type level (a forget-and-recover lemma analogous to $\PicardFunctorAb.\mathrm{forgetCompare}$). This lemma is not strictly required for $\genus$ but is useful for downstream consumers; it can be added in a follow-up iteration.
178	  \item Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, $\finrank_k H^i(C, \mathcal F) < \infty$) remains the deep work to come, but is now expressible inside Mathlib's standard $\Module\,k$ API.
179	\end{itemize}
180	
181	\section{Mathlib gap}
182	
183	After Section~\ref{sec:scheme_toModuleKSheaf} is implemented, this chapter has no remaining Mathlib gap. The construction reuses only the following established Mathlib pieces:
184	
185	\begin{itemize}
186	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasSheafify}, \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard}, and the abelian/$\Linear\,k$ enrichment on $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probes; underlies Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext}).
187	  \item \lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.\Gamma SpecIso}, \lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Hom.app}, \lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.presheaf} (existing Mathlib API for the structure morphism and the structure-sheaf restriction maps).
188	  \item \lstinline{Algebra.compHom} / \lstinline{RingHom.toAlgebra} (algebra-from-ring-map).
189	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Presheaf.isSheaf_iff_isSheaf_forget} (concrete-category sheaf criterion; transfers the sheaf condition between $\CommRingCat$ and $\ModuleCat\,k$).
190	\end{itemize}
191	
192	Nothing genuinely new is required from Mathlib. The iter-006 plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe verifies the full $\sim$80-LOC construction end-to-end against Mathlib \texttt{b80f227}.
